net.sourceforge.waters.model.compiler.context

Class RangeEstimator

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sourceforge.waters.model.base.DefaultProxyVisitor
      • net.sourceforge.waters.model.module.DefaultModuleProxyVisitor
        • net.sourceforge.waters.model.compiler.context.RangeEstimator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ProxyVisitor, ModuleProxyVisitor

    public class RangeEstimator
extends DefaultModuleProxyVisitor

    An evaluation component to estimate the range of simple expressions.

    Given the ranges of variables in a VariableContext, the range estimator propagates these ranges through all operators to give an estimate of the range of an expression. For example, if x and y are variables with range 1..3, then the estimated range of x+y is 2..6.

    The range estimator does not make any attempt to evaluate array indexes. The range of an indexed expression such as a[2] is looked up in the context, by no attempt is made to evaluate i in a[i]. Likewise, primed (next-state) subexpressions are not evaluated.

    The range estimate of an expression with undefined or variable-indexed identifiers is returned as null, i.e., unknown.

    Author:
    Robi Malik

      • estimateRange

        public CompiledRange estimateRange(SimpleExpressionProxy expr,
                                   VariableContext context)
                            throws EvalException
        Computes the estimated range of an expression in a given context.
        Parameters:
        expr - The expression to be evaluated.
        context - The context that provides bindings to identifiers.
        Returns:
        The range of possible values of the given expression, or null if the range cannot be estimated due to undefined identifiers. The result may be an over-approximation, meaning that not all values in the returned range can actually be obtained by assignment of values to variables.
        Throws:
        EvalException - to indicate a problem while evaluation the expression. Exceptions may be thrown even for values that cannot actually be obtained, e.g., when a Boolean operator is given an integer argument whose estimated range contains values other than 0 or 1.
